No liberating amendment for Tymoshenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian Parliament today refused the request to abolish the provisions on the basis of which the opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been convicted in the context of an amendment to the Criminal Code.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned Minister of Expression, was rejected by the Members at the second reading of the request for a reduction in the penalties for economic offences.
In October, Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for the conclusion of an allegedly negative contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not yet in force, and in December the appeal of the convicted is to be negotiated in court.
Timoshenko himself refers to the judgment as the political revenge of the regime and in the West the trial also made the suspicion of the court's bias rise.
The request to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Minister of Expression was sentenced, from the Criminal Code was supported by 147 Members.
226 votes would have been necessary for its adoption.
