V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The originally carefree ride is made by a series of completely avoidable, dilettantian errors for the routine journey to the early shift.
Although it was possible to fulfil the ambitions for the most part, what's the use of it when obviously no one was in the mood to do a little more.
Even before he came to the shop tables, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" raised high expectations.
After all, he promised to move the year-old "Need for Speed" game series back into a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples, he actually did not seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about how the adapted passages are, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are already used to it at NFS, in the end, much is different than you had expected.
Of course - it is potentially quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is reduced by some unnecessary errors that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So it's actually no longer a mistake, but rather a sign of a in principle imperceptible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure begins very well.
For the first time, one is introduced into history, whose main character Jack has certain problems of personal character; the only solution seems to be to take part in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, that is, on the west coast, you sit on the steering wheel - with the task of being first in New York.
The basic idea includes a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting ways.
You don't have a moment of the impression that game would always offer the same thing.
Some environments can be seen in a very pretty way, even though the technical level of the graphic does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the journey through the desert, through the autumn landscape or high up through the deep-snow landscape, is visually very pleasant.
Every now and then, untypical elements bring a little change in the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert tower that restricts the view.
In the mountains, in turn, one must take care of the hell that one is not spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well in a row.
It's just a few, but it's enough.
For a while, you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stop clock), then you still expect a personal duel with a single opponent.
And for that, the police are also interfering, who wants to screw up the whole thing.
A novelty is the passage where Jack leaves the car.
This is more about some interactive animations where Jack is fleeing from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are much less such passages in the game than one would expect (in concrete terms only three).
In the end, this is more to the advantage of the matter, because this element has at least no chance of getting boring - it is one of the elements that make the game more varied in the context of the above.
The driving model is in the footboards of the previous parts.
In other words, from today's point of view, it does not tear out trees, but on the other hand it could not be said that it is bad.
If you're looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But the local driving model will continue to be quite fair to an action-charged race, even though one could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in good order.
Real problems only come up after some time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite O.K.
It's hard to expect a game of this kind to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you don't know how the car behaves before any impact on any object, it's obviously not all right.
Typical example: When the car is overtaken or passed by the car, it is only easy to "strip" the other car in some places, but in other, almost identical situations you get into the slingshot and turn wild pirouettes.
Or the car is about to go to pieces.
Thanks to the Restart system, it doesn't matter any more, it's always annoying.
The restarts are so solved: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then the game throws you back to the last point of view of the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
When you have exhausted it, it all starts from the beginning.
So the restarts are more of a tool, in case something doesn't work, but you don't have to rely on it.
Sometimes, however, the restart does not even help, there is nothing else but to learn the critical section from the head.
It is very unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, have to go through in a very specific way, otherwise you just don't fit through.
In other places you always meet in the same configuration at the appropriate place "civil" cars, whether you come first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly annoying in situations when you see that the opponent comes by two coming cars before you play, but until you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive them around or brake them.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed so that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The counterparties have other advantages.
In the whole game there are a few places where you are always overtaken in the same place by the same opponent and here again without regard for the time.
This is the most crazy thing to do at the end of the game on the long bridge that is happening in the opposite direction.
The opponent must obviously overtake you here to the devil.
And if he's already in front of you, he'll take the view of you, of course, so that you start driving your own car in Kump a few times.
Of course - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it will quickly deprive you of the joy of the game.
And that's a pity, because despite a simpler driving model, the game is generally quite entertaining and sometimes so active that you almost don't know where your head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what's "to blame" - the concept of fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the change of car during the races.
One must not miss the gas stations on the track, because it is right here that you can change the car, although in most cases the car that you have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight motorways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of game history goes also the task mode (challenges) - the races in the individual locations you know from history.
Here there are not only medals, but also experience points for the own profile, which is common to the tasks (challenges) and the history.
In order to get to the higher level of the driver, different objects have to be opened: from the car, to the background for the profile.
This is connected to the online autologue function, which, among other things, compares its own results with those of other players and also provides for other collective functions.
One of the other ununderstandable cutters is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you get by car into a subway tunnel (because of me), where you ride on the rails in the dark (because of me).
On the tacho there are numbers between 150 a 200 km / h (because of me), but there comes a subway from the back and drives a uncompromising to scrap.
In our editorial office we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is not a major but at least the visual overall impression is in most cases quite appealing and here and there even brilliant.
It is all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the repetitive frequency is getting slower and this is sometimes rather dramatic.
This, however, is particularly true of the accidents involving a large number of people, where a continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The sound reproduction is as far as O.K. and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to address a scale as wide as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack a lá "of everyone" was created - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game were not reduced by the total unnecessary errors mentioned, we could have said with the chest tone of the conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game looks kind of unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but one should be prepared to make these mistakes with the power of airport lights in your eyes.
Concert of the "Students of the Samten Revolution" with vocal sembles of the Charles University
The Festival Festa Academica now offers for the third time the addition of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Samtenen Revolution and this, together with the music experience.
In the course of the festival, the twenty chors of science and higher education will be presented.
The festival focuses on the two concerts that take place on November 17.
"The Charles University has a big share in the festival."
"Among the participants is also the choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanist Studies and in the Festival Committee is also the Rector Václav Hampl," led the head of the organization team, Jakub Čaloun.
The absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of school teachers, which takes place on November 17 from 2 pm on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes the composition of the important Czech jazz Karel Růžička "Celebration Jazz Mass."
In the evening, the concert "Students of the Samten Revolution" (Studeny sametu) takes place in the gala rooms of the people's house in Vinohrady, where there are also university choirs, does not exclude the choirs of the Charles University.
Festa Academica is the goal not only to celebrate the World Student Day and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Samten Revolution, but to present choral music to the public at the highest level and to promote the creative cooperation of young people.
The main event is the association of Czech choirs in cooperation with the Johannes Kepler-Gymnasium.
Bohuslav Svoboda, the mayor of the capital Prague and Václav Hampl, the rector of the Charles University, took over the patronage of the entire event.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and in Pardubice.
The schedule also includes numerous music meetings, student happings, matinees and other events.
Detailed information can be found on the website of the festival www.festaacademica.cz
