IBM history: From cheese cutter to all-round flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines), founded in New York a hundred years ago, had a very complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was only taken over in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later company IBM was the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies such as the famous prick card watches to register the start and end of the work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Rantett Flint, who was also the chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
This leader then even put the founders of IBM in the shadows - based on Watson's ideas to this day the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson was the head of the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began to manufacture and sell all possible machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash.
In the first four decades of Watson's leadership, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable for the company that he was in the head chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM technicians and computers helped to lead NASA flights to space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
