Travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five state travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies sold only travel to the socialist East Bloc countries, and to the West at that time only chosen ones were allowed.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A simple exception was the period 1962-1972, when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed citizens of the Eastern bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovakia) to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered travel to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
It was a long way from the point of view of the matter.
The so-called foreign exchange commitment - the condition for an exit to the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange agreement it would have been impossible to obtain the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a journey to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that continues to this day.
The velvet revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on the foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, of which one is no longer aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 at all, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation was lifted to the neighbouring Western European countries, resulting in a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone at least wanted to have been there a few days.
For example, the Czech vacationers slept in the tent in the park when travelling to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension at that time.
A typical feature of the trip abroad from Czech was a trunk packed with canned, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely replaceable Czech krone - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of living and, as a result, the average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to prepare regular travel through charter flights after 1997, which made it possible to negotiate volume discounts, which was an incredible reduction compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the US, already had unsolicited payments with all the world's highly developed countries, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-velvet" travel came in 2000, when the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was made to Thailand thanks to the high demand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft have been flying every year with Czech passengers in far-away sunny countries; this year, you can fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
To the 100 thousand Czechs travel every year to exotic countries!
Another important moment in the epoch, which marked our "post-revolutionary" development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitely led our country to join the world's highly developed countries.
In 2008, the Czechs spent for the first time more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 thousand CZK per capita for a single holiday stay including the cost of the holiday.
