By Julia Statek
Paddling pools in Ufo-Optics, Prunkpools in Budapest: Those who travel through Europe can experience their blue miracle - and after a city tour or a hike, the tired legs rest in sprinkling pools.
A book shows where wellness is most beautiful in the water.
When Iris Meder went on a search trip over the past one and a half years, one in her luggage could not be missing: her bathing suit.
Lying back on the water, she looked high in artfully designed domes, she swam in front of marble-putts waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and amazed at the acrically restored Art Nouveau pools.
If she found a bath, she took it in flight in her notebook - with good details about the construction and history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools explored architecture historian Meder in this way - and now presents her in her recent book "Bathing Freiden": Volksswinhallen in Munich, historical swimming palace in the Black Forest, "Hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Through 13 countries, she led her "journey to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and each one city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
She doesn't have much to do with sport, says Meder - only in the water is that different.
The only thing that is annoying is that swimming fans have to get away with blue tiles and chlorinated stink, while joggers can breathe in the bewitching scent of spruce forests or listen to happy bird-wits in the park.
"I was wondering one day why swimming pools must always be so ugly," says the Meder living in Vienna.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
In the spring pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in bathrooms is so great because all the senses are served, Meder says.
And when the builders have made a lot of effort, swimming halls can be a real touch of eye: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in bathrooms."
"It is transparent on the one hand, but it reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
The small-format picture book "Bahnfreiden" provides information on the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases on 190 pages - but above all makes the desire for a jump into the blue.
The pool collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens in her research in Hungary.
In addition to the magnificent healing baths, such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, it found a nitrates-containing water in an ancient Karst cave (a cave in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath, the basin of which is filled with alkaline water and located in a bottle-like building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: While one has in mind the whole city from the Zurich Dachbad, one can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which one can watch the driving on the ski slopes.
The most extraordinary pool design, perhaps, awaits guests in Längenfeld: The Aquadome Ötztal looks like a Ufo just landed in the Alps.
From three up-open bowls it steals in the winter, while in the background the mountains of the Oetztal rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool the pool collector Meder the smell of chlorine rose in the nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulphur, in the Árpád bath in the Hungarian Békescsaba it stinks so much of fuel oil, which is hardly believed to have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrogencarbonate-containing healing water, which is almost black and whose slag is stuck to the skin as soon as you can slip into the pool - a wellness experience of the special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing places: when she wanted to visit the outdoor and sun swimming pool in the Czech bath of Luhatschowitz, she found a closed terrain.
The bathroom, designed by the architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902, has now been closed.
When Meder took a look through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing between the tiles.
On the other hand, the fall has been counteracted by a charming swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
Three phases of the construction have already been completed; it is possible to discover not only neoromaniac elements that come from the times of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since the careful modernisation in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favorite swimming pool of the pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because it was originally from the Black Forest.
