For the implementation, Kishanitz was the ideal occupation.
Not only because Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna had been sensitively redesigned and expanded and won the competition, but because he studied at the University of Vienna in Schwanzer and the pavilion was a "huge important place" for him, where he had seen the exhibitions "almost every weekend."
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost in generosity and lightness during his transfer to Vienna and its use.
There were far greater problems with the current conversion: the building was "an energy slingshot," says Kishanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, glass fibre-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold-bridge steel carriers have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been renovated.
Two lower floors brought space for the new use, a sewn-down light ditch between the house and the street provides for exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail pavilion.
