Climate adversity slowed the economy down
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is in the government, unemployment and undeclared work increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investment fell and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who called himself the initiator of change and raised great hopes for economic growth, is in the government. However, as a result of the climatic adversity, growth cannot be mentioned, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators have deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused millions of losses in agriculture, but also set close limits to the growth of the state economy and in the first quarter of the year caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6%. This is mainly due to the historical decline of agricultural development by 31.16%, which has had an impact on other sectors of the economy.
According to a report on the effects of the frost, published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustainable (the Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582 000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03% were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has led to a continuous increase in unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geographie observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, as between January and March, 55 053 people in Sinaloa had no employment, equivalent to 4.53% of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate increased to 5.28% and from July to September to 6.19%, resulting in 74 000 unemployed people in Sinaloa, which is 18 969 more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
The year's unemployment in Sinaloa is due to several factors. The economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented that the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are seeing is an increase in unemployment, which is related to several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market as a result of the cuts in money laundering legislation adopted in Congress, because it is not easy for those who are illegally raising dollars to work for themselves, to invest it or to use it for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment also has a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country for work abroad, especially in the United States, has fallen, which is due on the one hand to the problems of entry and, on the other hand, because it is also difficult to find work there. These people stay here and look for work, which increases unemployment," he says.
undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if we take into account the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, covers 60.38% of those employed in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
The low wages, the lowest in the whole of Mexico, come to unemployment and undeclared work, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Office for Labour and Social Care in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos until September, much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in FDI
In addition to the reduction in economic activity and increasing unemployment, in 2011, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) over the last ten years is recorded. According to the Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI was 630 597 dollars from January to June, a fall of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period last year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Authority for Economic Development), for its part, has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In the light of the economic crisis, the state government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos at the National Congress in July to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy. The state congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive impact of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be found by November.
Reactions
The first year of the government, Mario López Valdé, made it clear for the representatives of the business community.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of the Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), said that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year. It is important to work hard to regain the area that has been lost this year and in 2012 we have to double our efforts. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well-agreed government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events like the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development difficult and slow.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the most important effects is a slow economy that is not sufficiently moving to create an economic dynamic that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will complete the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefine vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexican Association of Entrepreneurs) in Sinaloa, said that the state must be encouraged to become more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme to redefine the country's economic vocation and line, because it is important to activate all the material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There's a lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that would better guide the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas where we can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
