The Court approves the transition to digital television in Mexico in 2015
The conversion of the analogue to digital signals has been one of the most important changes in the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional actions filed by the Senate and the House of Deputies against the Presidential Decree and, by virtue of the need to forward the switch from analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015, due to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his powers when he issued the bill on the details of switching to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate, as it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes in order for the court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
In the project for the action, which was prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, since the regulations concerning radio and television are the responsibility of the Comisión Federal de Telesomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Telecommunications Commission in Mexico), which is why the decree would be contrary to the hierarchical principles and the law's reserved rights.
In favour of the project only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Legislative Decree. After the adoption of the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Legislative Decree and ceased all activities to set up the digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the action brought by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the debate on the project, which was also the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his contribution, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the project's arguments, in the sense that the country government should not regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration with general rules.
"I do not believe that if we were to do this, the independence of the regulatory body would be affected." She also recalled that, for constitutional reasons, the central government is responsible for the planning of strategic policies, such as the telecommunications sector, because it is responsible for the state affairs.
The replacement of the analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years around the world, and it results in a better use of the radioelectric spectrum, an increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the transition, she said, was a postponement of the use of digitisation, which was a decision in the public interest, which had not only technical aspects, "because it covered economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "made the action of the whole system necessary, according to the principle of economic governance by the state they included a group of features that put the Constitution in the hands of the central government."
It recalled that many countries in the world had already implemented the digital transition, through the government, even though they had highly specialised institutions.
It could not be concluded that the government would intervene in the powers of the Congress by issuing the contested decree, because the laws adopted by the legislative would be respected, "she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballot in Michoacán is considered
According to PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is almost 27%, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of individual ballot counting is a reality this year in the elections in Michoacán, because according to the data provided by the Programa de Consultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the presidential elections is almost 27%, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074.
In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just on 9 November the electoral office had adopted a number of rules to harmonise local rules with the reforms of the states in election.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, his electoral law, or his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they had not entered into force in this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the government court within the time limits provided for, arguing that they had no objections to it.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional action brought by the local legislature and assessed the State Representative's vote on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal," as he did not have the right to "decide on it or to veto it."
In an interview with María de los Ángeles Llanderal on the possibility of the individual counting of votes, María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM would now allow the local election authority to count the votes in part or in full.
For example, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted. The results of the minutes do not agree; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not in fact available or are not in possession of the chairman of the election committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total number of fully completed ballot cards may be made if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the second-place winner, equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an express request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the above-mentioned candidates.
The vote counting may also be made in its entirety if, after the completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal or less than one percent, provided that an express request is made by a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the election packages which have been subject to partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between the first and second places is almost 0.16%, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
