The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy tomorrow to present to him the new government which is to face the crisis that has led Italy to the edge of the economic collapse.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy tomorrow to present to him the new government which is to face the crisis that has led Italy to the edge of the economic collapse.
A communication from the President's Palace announced that the Monti appointed on Sunday would meet with the President, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm the formation of the government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed of a majority of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new Prime Minister will take office.
Monti said he would present to the President the results of the talks with the political parties on the formation of government.
"I would like to reaffirm my absolute confidence in the ability of our country to cope with these difficult times," said the former EU Commissioner to the journalists.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "frame is now well set," he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than normal. Meanwhile, Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has put the cost of debt at an intolerable level.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must adopt a hard austerity package called for by the European politicians in order to regain the increased confidence in Italy.
The pressure on the rush that is being exerted on Monti has been exacerbated by the fluctuating market situation, which has caused the Italian government bonds to be charged with 7% interest for 10 years, in line with the situation in which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European rescue aid.
Emma Marcegaglia, President of the Italian Confederation of Industry Confindustria, told the press after a meeting with Monti, "We said we would support this government in all our efforts."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
The chances of success of Monti were significantly increased by the support of the party PDL of Silvio Berlusconi, who had to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
"We believe that the efforts of the professor Monti are intended to achieve good results," said Angelino Alfano, Secretary of the Central-Right Party.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is essential, because so far many of its members have spoken out against a majority of technocrats government that is currently forming Monti.
Support from Parliament
The new government of Monti needs strong parliamentary support to implement the probably unpopular austerity measures.
Resistance to its efforts or the delay in the reforms could once again lead to a devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks is also under pressure with its indication that a failure of Monti is a disaster.
Monti started on Monday with his debates with political parties, trade unions and business associations as well as with youth and women's organisations.
The session is scheduled to be closed on Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who, in response to the crisis, launched an extremely rapid change of government.
After a short breath towards the end of the last week, when it became known that Berlusconi would resign, as a result of the uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister, the cost of the Italian government bonds has again reached critical limits.
A rescue of Italy with a state debt of EUR 1.8 trillion would be too much for the current EU umbrella.
