The quintet included Costa Rica in his tour to celebrate its twenty-year-old existence
"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that is realized"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, the bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam says that the band is prepared to give one of their best concerts in the National Stadium next Sunday.
They were expected for more than 20 years, but the band assures them that a dream will be realized for them when they play in Costa Rica.
The bassist and co-founder of the group, Jeff Ament, who gave Viva an exclusive interview from Brazil last week.
The band is located in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their twenty-year-old existence and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On this day, they will be performing at the National Stadium from 7.30 p.m. with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You will read an excerpt from the conversation, the full copy of which can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costarican fans a dream is realized when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what this means to your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that is also realized for us.
This is just the second time we have played in South and Central America, and so far it has been great.
I have only been to Costa Rica for a holiday. It is such a beautiful country that we will probably stay there a few more days.
It's exciting for us to take our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely devoted. They experience the days before the concert more intense.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for standing by our side all these years.
We took almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry to have taken so long until we get here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Isn't that a little pressure from your visit?
Some of the most great shows we have put down in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played on a few giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play there.
We love this country, we like to surf and are excited about the jungle. Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world for that.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone to Costa Rica and Nicaragua for surfing. Together with Mexico, these are excellent areas for surfing. In this way, we have learned about it, about people who love surfing.
With a look at the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the Costa Rica event?
Since we have never played there, we have no limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that is partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs. Each one likes another song, so the decision we will play is not easy.
When we record two or three songs that we haven't played for a long time, we can keep our concentration better and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs. Otherwise, they could be forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think that's why it's also for the audience.
With this tour you will celebrate your twenty-year history.
If you look back, will it be hard for you to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don't think any of us imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years.
We continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are excited about producing music.
We are lucky to be able to go to the places in the world we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean for you to take part actively in the birth of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of big bands.
We're good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and quite unusual when a movement comes out of a group of friends.
Sometimes a band comes out of a city, but it is unusual when five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw soundguards on their tour. We are still happy to be friends with them all and we are honored to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It is also very unusual that a band like yours has stayed together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) came to us 13 years ago. This alone is much more time than many bands do.
First of all, I think we all appreciate being alive and, in addition, we take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give each individual the freedom to experiment.
One of them trusts the other and his music. We could not be better.
Your relationship to glory has not always been easy. On the other hand, thanks to your success, you could always do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we've grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it is too easy to fall into this game with huge masses of people who love your music.
As long as you think that people have come for the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has created without being a famous rock star. We never cared about that.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we have written very good songs and in the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think of what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, to laugh together and to talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The national band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos of several groups and we liked this band the best. Therefore we are curious to see what Las Roberta can offer live. It will be exciting.
Why do you always change the text of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing he can think of.
Who were you influenced by as a bass player?
From so many +
The first to think of me are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassist I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it's no longer a fashion show?
I don't think we all feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think it's great, because it's worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney make better music now than ever.
At first, her music was darker, now it's more positive.
Why?
This is interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a little light-headed, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe, which are classified as very dark songs, even though they have something positive in themselves.
The tears came to both of them when I heard Ed play them. It's very dark songs.
I think when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life - for example, if you lose a family member or a friend - that your artistic work and your music and these two songs clearly affect that for me.
But I also think that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
