Fujimori returned to the hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was sent to a public hospital on Tuesday to investigate the muscle loss of his legs, informed his home doctor.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is 25 years in prison for violating human rights during his reign (1990-2000), has several diseases, including tongue cancer, which is operated four times and under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, Congressman and his personal doctor, told the TV that Fujimori would be studied in the Peruvian hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas for three days to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower body parts.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons. Nevertheless, he did not wish it because he thought he was innocent.
It has been operated four times on tongue cancer and has lost 18 kilos of weight. In addition, there are other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and blood problems in the legs, the doctor counted.
Since September 2007, Fujimori has been located at the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la policía.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squadron of the Peruvian army, which was in secret during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official secondment, led by the Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón the next Wednesday. According to the Uruguayan president, this will be the highlight of his booked schedule with politicians, business people and a meeting with the collective of the Uruguayan living in Mexico.
The meeting of both presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries," the President of the South American country announced on its website.
According to the local media, Mujica is looking for the support of Calderón for the incident with France, when the French head of government, Nicolas Sarkozy, put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in Cannes, France.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries that still act as tax havens from the international community, which was rejected by Uruguay and led to a request from his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group consisting of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world. Since January of this year, there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid double assessment with the South American country.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has tried to speed up the implementation of agreements for the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which includes countries that have not introduced all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
At the business level, a free trade agreement has been in place between Mexico and Uruguay since 2004, which has contributed to the growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
