Asphalt from the UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, developed with polymers modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs of the road surface were to be taken into account, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200 000 potholes if the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (the city area of the valley of Mexico) would break out, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warning and assured that if the laying and maintenance of the asphalt cover would be appropriate, the number of potholes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Potholes from a Technical Perspective," which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing modified asphalt with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climate, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus to avoid the occurrence of impact holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the most heavy part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, of which a part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other part a low - the so-called Malthenes. Together they give the road surface its characteristic tentelastic behaviour.
Tensile behaviour of asphalt means that at high temperatures of almost 180 ° C it behaves like a liquid, at 120 ° C it is very tactile and at 50 ° C it is almost firm, while at very low temperatures it becomes fragile.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of a flexible road surface, composed of six material layers, of which the last three were asphalt.
Between the top layers there is a wear layer of asphalt consisting of small stones, bonded in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer, had been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of power in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he said, "a last layer is designed, the so-called bearing layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
As this layer is in contact with the vehicle handles, it requires a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it has to produce friction.
The most forces received and distributed by this road surface also require an appropriate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, in particular humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to be taken into account, especially the water, "he said," because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes wet, water penetrates into the layer and it is difficult to escape again. This causes a softening of all the layers of the road surface and therefore the appearance of impact holes.
When a hole is created, "he said," the cover layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only then affected, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained in the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs. "
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) said that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road cover must always be in relation to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is respected in order to avoid frequent impact holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries and with which the potholes could be easily repaired without applying high temperatures.
