All this explains the broad smile of the many Gazprom managers in Lubmin about the gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technology.
The underwater line is made of steel with concrete coating, which is intended to protect it from ship's anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, in about 200 m depth.
During their construction, mining fields dating from the Second World War had to be removed.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed in a cautious way," said Jens Müller, spokesman for the Nord Stream company.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long line of metal, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which is interrupted over the entire length by nothing: neither valves, nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project managers have not been able to do so, as the Swedes were not keen to see a Russian state company permanently settle at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of a disaster, we close the gas pass in less than a minute," specified Jens Müller.
In the case of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline is then released into the air.
However, this case is considered by the designers to be only little likely, as the weld seams were estimated to have a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured by both an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation purposes by a seagoing ship, and by a device that circulates inside the gas pipeline.
It has the form of a cigar, with a diameter of one meter, is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is moved by the gas pressure.
After three complete days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on the possible deformations of the metal on its arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without even having to undergo the least repair.
The gas circulation is simply guaranteed by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have united their forces to implement this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
In addition, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated (each of 15.5%), as are the Dutch gas company and the French group GDF Suez (each of 9%).
These five companies have formed a company group called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It has its seat in Zug in Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom has then rented the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company, to an extended twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real volume of gas is," specified Jens Müller.
The financing of gas transmission was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amount was 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are committed to recovering their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
